r sorting options plus the default behavior for null and out-of-range values, which all correctly map to USER_ID.\n\nThe SELECT statement has a trailing comma in the source that the knowledge file simplified away, which is fine. I'm also noting that the VariableInSyntaxConvertor class explicitly doesn't validate SQL syntax, so minor formatting differences like that aren't a concern for this implementation.\n\nThe knowledge file includes the same warning about SQL validity that appears in the source. The BasicSqlParameterParser section correctly references the variable condition, IN, and ORDER BY syntax convertors in both places. Looking at the structure, the source document has subsections a through e under a class definition heading, but the knowledge file consolidates all of this into a single section s1, which is acceptable since the content is cohesive even if lengthy. Looking at the remaining hints in the index, I see the annotation handlers and various SQL feature categories are all accounted for. Comparing against the source code, I notice the interface names like `SqlParameterParser` and `SqlConvertor` aren't explicitly listed as hints, though their implementations are—and the annotation names themselves (`@CurrentDateTime`, `@UserId`) also aren't included, only their handler classes. I'm seeing that the knowledge file is missing these three annotation names as hints, which counts as a minor finding. Moving on to check the `no_knowledge_content` validation—that's set to false so I can skip it. Now I'm compiling the findings: there's a critical omission around VariableInSyntaxConvertor where four key points about literal handling and SQL comment restrictions aren't documented in the knowledge file. I need to verify which converter these constraints actually apply to by checking the RST table structure more carefully. The bullet points about literal handling and lack of SQL comment support seem to be nested within VariableInSyntaxConvertor based on the indenta